<p>"Frameless glass curtains" sounds like a contradiction in terms — surely curtains are soft? But the name has stuck, and it's quite apt: these glass panels move and fold like a curtain, slid open and closed on a single overhead track. If you've admired the clean, unobstructed terraces on Marbella apartments and wondered how they do it, this is the system.</p>

<h2>How do frameless glass curtains work?</h2>

<p>The system is elegantly simple: tempered glass panels (typically 8, 10, or 12mm thick depending on height) hang from a stainless steel track fixed to the ceiling of the terrace. Each panel has a pivot roller at the top that runs in the track. The panels are connected to each other at the sides with neoprene seals, but without aluminium frames between them — hence "frameless".</p>

<p>When you want to open the terrace, you push the panels to one or both sides, where they "stack" (fold accordion-style) and park flat against the wall. The whole opening can be cleared in 30–60 seconds. When you want protection, you slide them back, and optional side locks click into place to secure the panels against wind.</p>

<p>In motorised systems, a tubular motor integrated into the track does all this at the press of a button or a phone app command.</p>

<h2>The advantages</h2>

<p><strong>Unobstructed views:</strong> Without vertical aluminium frames between panels, the view through closed glass curtains is almost like looking through a window with no dividers. For sea view or golf view properties, this is genuinely valuable.</p>

<p><strong>100% opening:</strong> No other fixed terrace enclosure opens as completely. When stacked to the side, the panels take up minimal space (typically 15–20cm per panel), leaving the full width of the terrace open.</p>

<p><strong>Reversible and non-invasive:</strong> The only permanent installation is the track anchored to the ceiling. There is no drilling into walls, no modification to the building's structure. The system can be completely removed without trace — valuable for renters, or for property owners in communities with strict rules.</p>

<p><strong>Low maintenance:</strong> Tempered glass doesn't fade, rot, or rust. Rinse with fresh water weekly (important near the sea — salt deposits build up), and apply silicone spray to the tracks once a year. That's essentially it.</p>

<p><strong>Community approval:</strong> Because the system is reversible and nearly invisible from outside, it's the enclosure type most likely to get approved at a community of owners meeting. We're seeing many communities in Marbella, Estepona, and Fuengirola that have voted to allow glass curtains for all residents as a standardised solution.</p>

<h2>The limitations</h2>

<p><strong>Not a sealed enclosure:</strong> Frameless glass curtains don't seal hermetically. In heavy rain with strong wind, some water ingress between panels is possible, especially on exposed terraces. If your terrace faces directly into the prevailing wind and rain, a semi-framed system or aluminium carpentry may be more appropriate.</p>

<p><strong>Limited thermal and acoustic insulation:</strong> The neoprene seals between panels provide some draught protection, but don't expect the performance of double-glazed aluminium carpentry. They're excellent for extending the comfortable use of a terrace by 4–6 months per year; they won't turn a terrace into a heated living room in mid-January.</p>

<p><strong>Height limitations:</strong> Standard frameless panels are practical up to about 2.5m high. Above that, the glass thickness increases significantly (12mm and above), which increases weight and cost. Very tall openings may be better served by a framed system.</p>

<h2>Is it worth installing?</h2>

<p>For Costa del Sol properties, the answer is almost always yes. A frameless glass curtain system that costs €1,500–€3,500 for a typical apartment terrace can add measurable value to the property (appraisers increasingly factor them in), significantly increase rental income potential by extending the comfortable outdoor season, and is simply a pleasure to use every day.</p>

